{"id": "act_1774902503828_zd2tsj", "timestamp": "2026-03-30T20:28:23.828Z", "source": "meeting", "type": "meeting_complete", "summary": "Meeting complete: Pre-Flight Resolver Pass 2: The recall rate measurement shows 71% average (83% narrow topics, 50% broad architectural). Pass 1 improvements (skip binaries, generic keyword filtering, dotfile support, root markdown boost) are committed. The remaining gap: broad meetings miss cross-cutting files like WORKER.md, SKILL.md, and API routes that implement the system being discussed. Three options for Pass 2: (A) Tag index integration ï¿½ use the existing tag index to find files referenced by decisions/actions in prior meetings on similar topics, (B) LLM-based ranking ï¿½ send the top 15 keyword matches to a fast model and ask it to pick the 5 most relevant, (C) Explicit file hints ï¿½ let the meeting topic include file paths that bypass the resolver entirely. Data: 7 total misses across 3 meetings, 4 false positives eliminated by Pass 1 fixes. Question: Is Pass 2 worth building now, and if so which approach? (4 decisions, 3 actions)", "linkedMeeting": "2026-03-30-design-review-pre-flight-resolver-pass-2-the-recall-rate-measurement-shows.md"}
{"id": "act_1774902667958_v8qldg", "timestamp": "2026-03-30T20:31:07.958Z", "source": "worker", "type": "code_change", "summary": "Improved pre-flight resolver: measured 71% recall rate, fixed false positives (binary files, generic keywords), added dotfile support, root markdown boost, and explicit file hints (Option C). 14 new tests.", "linkedMeeting": "2026-03-30-design-review-pre-flight-resolver-pass-2-the-recall-rate-measurement-shows.md"}
{"id": "act_1774903066186_bpgynr", "timestamp": "2026-03-30T20:37:46.186Z", "source": "meeting", "type": "meeting_complete", "summary": "Meeting complete: Post-Meeting Review UX: When you open a completed meeting, what should you see first? Currently you see the full transcript top-to-bottom. Should outcomes be more prominent? Should there be a TL;DR summary at the top? Consider: the viewer is primarily a post-meeting review tool, not a live dashboard. (5 decisions, 3 actions)", "linkedMeeting": "2026-03-30-design-review-post-meeting-review-ux-when-you-open-a-completed-meeting-wha.md"}
{"id": "act_1774903747469_wt0s2f", "timestamp": "2026-03-30T20:49:07.469Z", "source": "meeting", "type": "meeting_complete", "summary": "Meeting complete: Worker Session Continuity ï¿½ How should the autonomous worker maintain momentum across sessions? Current state: worker reads .council-worker-log.md for context, checks for nudges/tasks/planned meetings, runs meetings, builds features. Pain points: (1) worker log grows unbounded and must be trimmed, losing context, (2) no structured handoff between sessions ï¿½ just free-text log, (3) worker sometimes repeats analysis already done, (4) no way to mark work as partially complete. Question: What lightweight mechanism would give the worker better cross-session memory without adding complexity? (8 decisions, 5 actions)", "linkedMeeting": "2026-03-30-direction-check-worker-session-continuity-how-should-the-autonomous-worker-m.md"}
{"id": "act_1774904148436_s97rbv", "timestamp": "2026-03-30T20:55:48.436Z", "source": "worker", "type": "worker_run", "summary": "Completed pre-flight recall measurement (5/5) and implemented worker session continuity protocol", "detail": "Pre-flight recall: narrow topics 80%+, broad topics 25-50%. Tag index confirmed as not useful for file resolution (Option A rejected). Created .council-worker-state.json for cross-session handoff. Updated WORKER.md with session protocol. 5 meeting actions done, 1 open question resolved.", "linkedMeeting": "2026-03-30-direction-check-worker-session-continuity-how-should-the-autonomous-worker-m.md"}
{"id": "act_1774904474605_sr89yg", "timestamp": "2026-03-30T21:01:14.605Z", "source": "meeting", "type": "meeting_complete", "summary": "Meeting complete: Decision Discovery UX ï¿½ How Should Users Find Past Decisions? [app/meetings/MeetingList.tsx, lib/tag-index.ts, app/api/meetings/tags/route.ts]\n\nWith 47+ meetings and growing, finding past decisions is increasingly important. The tag index and recall API exist (recallByTopic, /api/meetings/tags?mode=recall) but have NO UI. Users must use MCP tools or manually open meetings.\n\nCurrent state:\n- Meeting list has title search, status filter, type filter chips\n- Tag summary shows counts (decisions: N, actions: N, open: N) in the sidebar\n- No way to search decision TEXT from the UI\n- No way to ask \"what did we decide about caching?\" without MCP\n- recallByTopic() does keyword matching across all tagged items\n- Tag index supports type filtering (decision/action/open)\n\nKey questions:\n1. Where should decision search live? New page? Inline in meeting list? Sidebar panel?\n2. Should it be full-text search or structured browse (by type, by date, by meeting)?\n3. How should results link back to the source meeting?\n4. Should the existing meeting search be enhanced to also search outcomes, or should decisions get their own surface?\n5. What is the minimum viable version that helps tomorrow morning? (6 decisions, 5 actions)", "linkedMeeting": "2026-03-30-design-review-decision-discovery-ux-how-should-users-find-past-decisions-a.md"}
